{{Infobox NRHP | name =Sons of Jacob Cemetery | nrhp_type = | image = | caption = |location=88th Ave. NE, {{convert|0.25|mi|km}} north of 67th St. NE, vicinity of [[Garske, North Dakota|Garske]] in [[Ramsey County, North Dakota]] | coordinates={{coord|48.389048|N|98.757746|W|display=title,inline}} | locmapin = North Dakota#USA | architect OR builder = | architecture = | added=June 5, 2017 | area = | mpsub = | refnum =100001035<ref name=weekly>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/nr/listings/20170609.htm |title=National Register of Historic Places Program: Weekly List|date=June 9, 2017 |publisher=[[National Park Service]]}}</ref> }} The '''Sons of Jacob Cemetery''' in rural [[Ramsey County, North Dakota]] was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2017. It was the cemetery of the '''Garske Colony''', a farming community of Jewish immigrant homesteaders which was founded in 1883 and operated until about 1925.<ref>[http://www.sojnorthdakota.org/#Garske Garske Colony]</ref>
Jewish homesteaders came from Russia, where they were not allowed to own land, and tried to survive in harsh conditions in North Dakota. Many built [[sod houses]] or tarpaper shacks to live in while attempting to prove their land claims for {{convert|160|acre|km2}} under the Homestead Act.
There once were nine rural Jewish cemeteries in North Dakota. The cemetery of the largest Jewish farming community in the state, the [[Ashley Jewish Homesteaders Cemetery]], was listed on the National Register in May 2015. The Garske one, the Ashley one, and one in Regan are the only three that are "not entirely overgrown" by 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bismarcktribune.com/news/state-and-regional/jewish-homesteader-cemetery-added-to-national-register/article_2f589489-0635-59b8-85a7-92f982188c82.html |title=Jewish homesteader cemetery added to national register |author=Carolyn Grueskin |publisher=[[Bismarck Tribune]] |date=June 21, 2017}}</ref>
